T = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | footnotes = }} The '''Xiangkhouang Plateau''' or '''Xiangkhoang Plateau''', also known in [[French language|French]] as '''Plateau du Tran-Ninh''' is a [[plateau]] in the north of [[Laos]]. The landscape is characterized by green mountains, rugged karst formations and verdant valleys with plenty of [[river]]s, caves and waterfalls. ==Geography== The [[Luang Prabang Range]], and the [[Annamite Range]] separate the plateau from [[Thailand]] and [[Vietnam]] respectively.<ref>''The Ancient and Classical History of Southeast Asia''</ref> The ranges of the plateau are [[sandstone]] and [[limestone]] mountains between 2000 and 2800 meters high (about 6561 and 9842 feet high). These have been heavily [[deforested]]. The highest mountain of [[Laos]], [[Phou Bia]], is located to the south of the Xiangkhoang. Altitudes within the plateau area may reach 1000 m.<ref>[http://www.clio.fr/CHRONOLOGIE/pdf/pdf_chronologie_laos.pdf Laos, Le « Pays du million d’éléphants »]</ref> Several tributaries of the [[Mekong]] drain in the plateau, such as the [[Nam Ngum]], [[Ngiap River|Ngiap]] and the [[Khan River]].<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/650799/Xiangkhoang-Plateau Encyclopædia Britannica - Xiangkhoang Plateau]</ref> The major town in the area is the capital of [[Phonsavan]]. The plateau gives its name to present-day [[Xiangkhouang Province]] in which Phonsavan is located.
==History== The plateau is the location of the [[Plain of Jars]], which is a collective name for several sites with funerary archeological remains nominated for UNESCO World Heritage status.<ref>[http://www.xieng-khouang.com/ Welcome to Xieng Khouang!] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111220014131/http://www.xieng-khouang.com/ |date=December 20, 2011 }}</ref>
The plateau is also one of the most heavily contaminated areas in the world from unexploded [[cluster munitions]] also called [[UXO]]. ==References== {{reflist}} ==External links== *[https://web.archive.org/web/20120502042815/http://www.worldmapsinfo.com/mapimage/laos.jpg Physical map of Laos] *[http://www.ifad.org/evaluation/public_html/eksyst/doc/prj/region/pi/laos/r256labe.htm Laos: Xieng Khouang Agricultural Development Project]
